compareTo

public int compareTo(java.lang.Object o)
compareTo compares this RecordIF object to the Object parameter, which also must be a RecordIF object, determining which object is before, the same, or after the other denoted by < 0, == 0, and > 0. Note: this class has a natural ordering that is inconsistent with equals. This condition only occurs when the RecordIF objects keyFields differ and a comparison would be inaccurate. The result in this default implementation of comparing two RecordIF objects with different keyFields is to return 0 (equal). This is to ensure stability if comparing the same two RecordIF objects by another field proves to be feasible, this will preserve the previous ordering on the objects.
Specified by:
compareTo in interface java.lang.Comparable
Parameters:
o - is a java.lang.Object (RecordIF object) used to compare in ordering with this RecordIF object.
Returns:
a integer value of < 0 if this RecordIF object should come before the Object parameter, == 0 if this RecordIF object has the same position as the Object parameter, or > 0 if this RecordIF object should come after the specified Object parameter.
Throws:
a - java.lang.ClassCastException if the Object parameter is not a valid RecordIF object.

public boolean containsValue(java.lang.Object value)
containsValue returns true if this map maps one or more keys to the specified value. More formally, returns true if and only if this map contains at least one mapping to a value v such that (value==null ? v==null : value.equals(v)). This operation will probably require time linear in the map size for most implementations of the Map interface.

entrySet

public java.util.Set entrySet()
entrySet returns a set view of the mappings contained in this map. Each element in the returned set is a Map.Entry. The set is backed by the map, so changes to the map are reflected in the set, and vice-versa. If the map is modified while an iteration over the set is in progress, the results of the iteration are undefined. The set supports element removal, which removes the corresponding mapping from the map, via the Iterator.remove, Set.remove, removeAll, retainAll and clear operations. It does not support the add or addAll operations.
Specified by:
entrySet in interface java.util.Map
Returns:
a set view of the mappings contained in this map.

public boolean equals(java.lang.Object o)
equals compares the specified object with this map for equality. Returns true if the given object is also a map and the two Maps represent the same mappings. More formally, two maps t1 and t2 represent the same mappings if t1.entrySet().equals(t2.entrySet()). This ensures that the equals method works properly across different implementations of the Map interface.

values

public java.util.Collection values()
values returns a collection view of the values contained in this map. The collection is backed by the map, so changes to the map are reflected in the collection, and vice-versa. If the map is modified while an iteration over the collection is in progress, the results of the iteration are undefined. The collection supports element removal, which removes the corresponding mapping from the map, via the Iterator.remove, Collection.remove, removeAll, retainAll and clear operations. It does not support the add or addAll operations
